    "text": "By Joedy McCreary, USA TODAY ,\n30 minutes ago Actor and former California Governor Arnold Schwarzenegger speaks, as he receives an honorary doctorate from the Hertie School, in Berlin, Germany, September 17, 2024. REUTERS/Liesa Johannssen Liesa Johannssen, REUTERS The claim: Image shows Arnold Schwarzenegger wearing anti-Trump T-shirt A Nov. 19 Threads post ( direct link , archive link ) appears to show actor and former California Gov. Arnold Schwarzenegger wearing a T-shirt mocking President-elect Donald Trump.\n“I didn’t vote for the McFelon,\" reads the message on the shirt, which also shows the McDonald’s golden arches logo beneath a graphic of Trump’s trademark hairstyle.\nThe post received more than 100 likes in three days. A similar post on Threads received thousands of likes before it was deleted. The image was also shared thousands of times on X, formerly Twitter .\nMore from the Fact-Check Team: How we pick and research claims | Email newsletter | Facebook page\nOur rating: Altered The image was digitally edited to add the anti-Trump message on Schwarzenegger’s shirt.\nSchwarzenegger's shirt blank in original image Schwarzenegger, a Republican, served as California's governor from 2003 to 2011 but supported Democratic Vice President Kamala Harris’ bid for president in the 2024 election.\nHe did not, however, pose while wearing a T-shirt with an anti-Trump slogan. The image in the Threads post was digitally altered to make it appear as if he did.\nFact check : 'Hitler Did Nothing Wrong' message edited onto Laura Loomer's photo\nSchwarzenegger posted the original image to Instagram on March 16. It shows him wearing a blank T-shirt and smiling as he poses alongside fellow bodybuilder Phil Heath in a gym. The background and the expression on the former governor’s face match those in the version shared to Threads. Heath is cropped out of the altered version of the image.\nThe slogan edited onto the T-shirt references Trump’s much-publicized love of fast food along with his conviction on 34 counts of falsifying business records to conceal a hush money payment to an adult film actress before the 2016 presidential election. His sentencing in that case, most recently scheduled for Nov. 26 , was postponed indefinitely on Nov. 22.\nSchwarzenegger gave Harris and her running mate, Minnesota Gov. Tim Walz, his endorsement in the presidential race, writing in an Oct. 30 X post \"I will always be an American before I am a Republican.\"\nUSA TODAY previously debunked similar images of political messages being edited onto clothing worn by public figures including musicians Taylor Swift and Kid Rock and former First Lady Michelle Obama .\nUSA TODAY reached out to multiple social media users who shared the image but did not immediately receive any responses.\nCheck Your Fact also debunked the claim.\nOur fact-check sources Arnold Schwarzenegger, March 16, Instagram post Thank you for supporting our journalism. You can subscribe to our print edition, ad-free app or e-newspaper here .\nUSA TODAY is a verified signatory of the International Fact-Checking Network, which requires a demonstrated commitment to nonpartisanship, fairness and transparency. Our fact-check work is supported in part by a grant from Meta .\nThis article originally appeared on USA TODAY: Schwarzenegger wore 'McFelon' T-shirt mocking Trump? No, image is altered | Fact check",
